---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Med-Surgical 41 — Mathias Hedding"
  description="Unfolding case study: Postoperative Wound Debridement with Diabetes and Heart Failure (MED-41)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/med-surgical/`}>Med-Surgical</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Med-Surgical 41 — Mathias Hedding</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Wound Care / Diabetes</span>
    <h1>Med-Surgical 41 — Mathias Hedding</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Postoperative Wound Debridement with Diabetes and Heart Failure</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Mathias Hedding, 62 years, Caucasian Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>Handoff Report</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the oncoming nurse on the medical-surgical unit. You receive handoff for Mathias Hedding, a 62-year-old Caucasian male with Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) and heart failure (HF). He is postoperative following wound debridement for a diabetic foot ulcer and sacral pressure injury. His wound dressing is in place and he is oriented.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Mathias Hedding</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>62 years · Male · Caucasian</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Wound debridement (diabetic foot ulcer / sacral pressure injury)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Medical History</th><td>Type 2 diabetes mellitus; heart failure</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Current status</th><td>Postoperative; oriented × 3; wound dressing in place</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Medications on MAR</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Clindamycin IV</strong> — <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span> wound infection coverage (C. diff risk)</li>
          <li><strong>Regular Insulin SQ</strong> — <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span> sliding scale (two-nurse check required)</li>
          <li><strong>Dextrose 50% (D50) IV</strong> — <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span> emergency hypoglycemia</li>
          <li><strong>Furosemide (Lasix) PO</strong> — loop diuretic for heart failure</li>
          <li><strong>Acetaminophen PO</strong> — adjunct pain management q4h</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Mathias is in bed, awake and oriented. He says, "My foot is sore, but I feel okay other than that." Wound dressing to foot and sacrum in place; no visible strike-through. He appears slightly edematous in both lower extremities.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do T2DM and heart failure interact to impair wound healing?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>T2DM impairs wound healing through:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Hyperglycemia impairs neutrophil function → weakened immune response to infection</li>
          <li>Peripheral vascular disease (PVD) → reduced blood flow to wound bed → inadequate O2 and nutrients</li>
          <li>Peripheral neuropathy → cannot feel wound forming or worsening</li>
          <li>Impaired collagen synthesis → slower wound closure</li>
          <li>High glucose environment is an ideal bacterial growth medium</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Heart failure adds:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reduced cardiac output → reduced peripheral perfusion → less O2 delivery to wound tissues</li>
          <li>Peripheral edema (especially feet) → tissue fluid compresses microvasculature → further impairs perfusion</li>
          <li>Together, HF + T2DM create a profoundly impaired wound healing environment — both must be managed simultaneously</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You assess Mathias's wounds and review the pressure ulcer staging…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Pressure Ulcer Staging</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Before assessing Mathias's wound dressing, you review the pressure ulcer staging system. His sacral wound was classified before debridement. Understanding staging guides dressing selection and intervention planning.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Pressure Ulcer Stages</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Description</th><th>Appearance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Deep Tissue Injury (DTI)</strong></td><td>Intact skin with persistent non-blanchable deep discoloration or blood-filled blister</td><td>Purple or maroon; may feel boggy or firm</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 1</strong></td><td>Non-blanchable erythema of intact skin</td><td>Red skin that does NOT turn white when pressed</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 2</strong></td><td>Partial-thickness skin loss involving epidermis and/or dermis</td><td>Shallow open ulcer or serum-filled blister; pink/red wound bed; no slough</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 3</strong></td><td>Full-thickness skin loss; subcutaneous fat visible</td><td>Crater-like; fat visible; slough/eschar may be present; no fascia exposed</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 4</strong></td><td>Full-thickness loss with exposed muscle, bone, tendon, or ligament</td><td>Bone/tendon/muscle visible; tunneling common</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Unstageable</strong></td><td>Full-thickness loss obscured by slough or eschar; depth unknown</td><td>Yellow slough or brown/black eschar covering wound base</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📍 Most Common Pressure Ulcer Locations</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Sacrum / coccyx</strong> — most common in bed-bound patients</li>
          <li><strong>Heels</strong> — especially in diabetic patients (neuropathy + vascular disease)</li>
          <li><strong>Greater trochanter</strong> — common in side-lying positions</li>
          <li><strong>Ischial tuberosities</strong> — common in sitting patients</li>
          <li><strong>Elbows</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Occiput (back of head)</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Ears</strong> — from nasal cannula or O2 mask</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          <p><strong>Repositioning Protocol:</strong> Turn q2h. Use <strong>30-degree lateral tilt</strong> (not full side-lying) — reduces trochanter pressure while offloading sacrum.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why do pressure ulcers form? What factors made Mathias high-risk?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pressure ulcer formation:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sustained pressure</strong> reduces blood flow → tissue hypoxia → cell death (necrosis)</li>
          <li><strong>Friction</strong> — skin rubbing against surface during repositioning damages superficial layers</li>
          <li><strong>Shear</strong> — deeper tissues shift while skin stays stationary (e.g., sliding down in bed)</li>
          <li><strong>Moisture</strong> — urine, perspiration, wound drainage macerate and weaken skin</li>
          <li><strong>Malnutrition</strong> — inadequate protein and calories impair tissue viability</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Mathias's high-risk factors:</strong> T2DM (peripheral neuropathy — cannot feel pressure; PVD — reduced perfusion), heart failure (peripheral edema → poor perfusion), immobility post-wound debridement.</p>
        <p><strong>Head of bed:</strong> Elevate no more than 30 degrees to minimize shear force over sacrum.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You perform a detailed postoperative wound assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Postoperative Wound Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You carefully remove Mathias's wound dressing to perform a full assessment. You document using the REEDA framework plus depth, size, and wound bed characteristics.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩹 REEDA Wound Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>R — Redness</th><td>Periwound erythema — assess if spreading</td></tr>
            <tr><th>E — Edema</th><td>Swelling at wound margins</td></tr>
            <tr><th>E — Ecchymosis</th><td>Bruising at or near wound site</td></tr>
            <tr><th>D — Drainage</th><td>Type, amount, color, odor (see below)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>A — Approximation</th><td>Wound edges together (closed) or gaping?</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Size</th><td>Measure L × W × D in cm at each dressing change</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <h3 style="margin-top:1rem;">🩸 Wound Drainage Types</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Appearance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Serous</td><td>Clear, watery — normal early healing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Serosanguineous</td><td>Pink/blood-tinged — normal early healing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sanguineous</td><td>Bright red — fresh bleeding</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Purulent</td><td>Yellow/green, thick, foul odor — infection</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🏥 Four Types of Debridement</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Method</th><th>Speed</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Surgical / Sharp</strong></td><td>Scalpel, scissors, curette in OR or wound clinic — most rapid; used for large/infected wounds</td><td>Fastest</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Mechanical</strong></td><td>Wet-to-dry dressings; wound irrigation; whirlpool — non-selective (can remove healthy tissue)</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Enzymatic</strong></td><td>Collagenase (Santyl) topically — selective; applied daily; needs moist environment</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Autolytic</strong></td><td>Moisture-retentive dressings (hydrocolloid, hydrogel) — body's own enzymes; selective; NOT for infected wounds</td><td>Slowest</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-info">
      <strong>🔑 Wound Bed Characteristics</strong>
      <p><strong>Granulation tissue</strong> — pink/red, bubbly, moist = healthy healing tissue ✓</p>
      <p><strong>Slough</strong> — yellow, stringy, necrotic tissue = requires debridement</p>
      <p><strong>Eschar</strong> — black/brown, hard, necrotic = requires debridement (surgical preferred)</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Mathias had surgical debridement — what is the nurse's role postoperatively?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Postoperative nursing role after surgical debridement:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Assess wound at each dressing change — document size, wound bed, drainage, periwound</li>
          <li>Maintain wound moisture balance — select dressing per wound type and provider/WOCN order</li>
          <li>Monitor for bleeding — surgical debridement can cause postoperative bleeding; assess dressing for saturation</li>
          <li>Pain management — pre-medicate before dressing changes; document response</li>
          <li>Infection surveillance — monitor for increasing redness, purulent drainage, fever, elevated WBC</li>
          <li>Positioning — continue 30-degree lateral tilt and q2h repositioning to prevent new pressure injuries</li>
          <li>Offload operative sites — no pressure on debrided foot; use heel protectors, positioning devices</li>
          <li>Coordinate with wound care nurse (WOCN) for dressing recommendations</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Mathias's blood glucose is checked and insulin is due on the sliding scale…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Hypoglycemia Risk Management</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Mathias has stress hyperglycemia post-debridement. His sliding scale insulin is due. However, he is eating poorly and you must carefully assess his hypoglycemia risk before and after insulin administration.</p>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 HIGH ALERT: Regular Insulin SQ — Double-Check Required</strong>
      <p>Insulin is a high-alert medication. ALWAYS obtain an independent double-check with a second RN before administration. Verify: right insulin type · right dose per sliding scale · right patient · right route · right time. Check blood glucose immediately before administering.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩸 Sliding Scale Insulin Process</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1</td><td>Check blood glucose q4–6h per order</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td>Verify current glucose against sliding scale parameters</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>Obtain independent double-check with second RN (HIGH ALERT)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4</td><td>Confirm patient will eat adequate meal; assess oral intake</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>Administer insulin per scale; rotate sites; document site</td></tr>
            <tr><td>6</td><td>Recheck glucose 1–2 hours post-administration; monitor for hypoglycemia</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Hypoglycemia Signs and D50 Response</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Signs of Hypoglycemia (BG &lt; 70 mg/dL)</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Shakiness, tremor</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Diaphoresis (sweating)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Confusion, altered mental status</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tachycardia, palpitations</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pallor; feeling of hunger</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-danger" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          <p><strong>D50 (Dextrose 50%) — HIGH ALERT</strong></p>
          <p>If Mathias is unresponsive or cannot swallow: D50 50 mL slow IV push per order. <strong>Ensure IV patency first — tissue necrosis risk if extravasation occurs.</strong> Recheck glucose 15 min after.</p>
          <p>If alert and able to swallow: 15 g fast carbohydrate (4 oz juice, glucose tabs) — 15/15 Rule.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>🔬 Clindamycin IV — C. diff Risk</strong>
      <p>Monitor for new-onset diarrhea, especially bloody or mucoid stools. Clindamycin is a high-risk antibiotic for <em>Clostridioides difficile</em> colitis. Report any diarrhea immediately — stop medication and notify provider. Patient teaching: complete full course; do not take antidiarrheals without provider approval.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does diabetes make wound debridement a higher-risk procedure?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Diabetes elevates risk in wound debridement because:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Stress hyperglycemia</strong> — surgical stress triggers cortisol and catecholamine release → blood glucose spikes → insulin required → hypoglycemia risk if NPO or poor oral intake</li>
          <li><strong>Impaired immune function</strong> — hyperglycemia prevents neutrophils from functioning normally → higher infection risk post-debridement</li>
          <li><strong>Poor vascular supply</strong> — PVD limits blood flow to debrided tissue → impaired healing and ischemia risk at surgical site</li>
          <li><strong>Peripheral neuropathy</strong> — Mathias may not adequately perceive post-debridement pain → complications may go unreported</li>
          <li><strong>Drug metabolism changes</strong> — diabetic nephropathy can accumulate medications</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You monitor Mathias's heart failure alongside his wound care needs…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Heart Failure + Wound Care Dual Management</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Mathias requires simultaneous management of heart failure and wound healing — conditions that directly compete with each other. Fluid overload worsens wound healing; inadequate fluid can impair tissue perfusion. You must balance both carefully.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>❤️ Heart Failure Monitoring</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Daily weight</th><td>Same time, same scale, same clothing — 1 kg gain = ~1 L fluid retained; report &gt;1 kg/day or &gt;2 kg/week</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Strict I&amp;O</th><td>Document all intake and output; report imbalance</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Edema assessment</th><td>Assess bilateral lower extremities — pitting edema = fluid in tissue = poor perfusion to wound</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Furosemide (Lasix)</th><td>Give in morning; monitor K⁺ (hypokalemia risk); assess BP before giving</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Potassium monitoring</th><td>Loop diuretics deplete potassium; hypokalemia impairs wound healing and increases cardiac dysrhythmia risk</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩹 Dressing Selection by Wound Type</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Wound Condition</th><th>Appropriate Dressing</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Dry necrotic wound</td><td>Hydrogel or hydrocolloid (add moisture)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wet / heavily draining</td><td>Foam dressing; alginate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Infected wound</td><td>Silver-containing dressing; antimicrobial</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Clean granulating wound</td><td>Non-adherent dressing; foam</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          <p><strong>🥗 Nutrition for Wound Healing:</strong> Protein 1.25–1.5 g/kg/day (collagen synthesis); Vitamin C (cross-linking); Vitamin A (epithelialization); Zinc (enzyme cofactor). Dietitian consult essential.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why does edema impair wound healing?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>How edema impairs wound healing:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Fluid accumulation in interstitial tissue increases the diffusion distance between capillaries and cells</li>
          <li>Oxygen and nutrients must travel farther to reach wound bed cells — inadequate delivery slows healing</li>
          <li>Edematous tissue compresses small capillaries → reduces microvascular blood flow to wound</li>
          <li>Elevated interstitial pressure also promotes bacterial growth (stagnant fluid = bacterial medium)</li>
          <li>Edema stretches and weakens wound edges — impairs approximation and closure</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Management in Mathias:</strong> Daily weight, strict I&amp;O, furosemide as ordered, leg elevation when sitting, compression stockings only if arterial perfusion is adequate.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your documentation and nursing diagnoses…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Nursing Diagnoses + SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Skin Integrity</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: open surgical wound post-debridement; T2DM impairing healing; peripheral edema from HF reducing wound perfusion</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Pain</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: patient report of foot soreness; surgical wound present; pre-medication required before dressing changes</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Unstable Blood Glucose</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: T2DM; receiving regular insulin sliding scale; postoperative stress hyperglycemia; risk of hypoglycemia if NPO or poor intake</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Excess Fluid Volume</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: heart failure diagnosis; bilateral lower extremity edema; on furosemide; daily weight monitoring required</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Infection</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: open surgical wound; T2DM-related immune compromise (hyperglycemia impairs neutrophil function); receiving Clindamycin IV</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Mathias's Wound and Blood Glucose</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>I am calling about Mathias Hedding, a 62-year-old male who is postoperative day [X] from wound debridement. I am reporting [assessment finding: wound changes / blood glucose of X / signs of fluid overload].</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>He has Type 2 diabetes and heart failure. He is on Clindamycin IV, regular insulin sliding scale, furosemide, and acetaminophen. His blood glucose this morning was [value]. His wound appears [describe bed, drainage, size]. His weight compared to yesterday is [increased/stable/decreased].</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>I am concerned about [worsening wound infection / hypoglycemia risk — blood glucose trending down after insulin / fluid overload — weight up X kg from yesterday] given his dual diagnosis of T2DM and heart failure.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting [wound care consultation / blood glucose recheck in 30 min / potassium level / repeat weight]. Should furosemide dose be adjusted? Dietitian consult needed for wound healing nutrition support.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Clindamycin IV</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Lincosamide antibiotic</td>
          <td>Infuse at correct rate (1 mL/hr or per dilution protocol — rapid infusion causes arrhythmias and hypotension). <strong>Major risk: C. difficile colitis</strong> — monitor for bloody/mucoid diarrhea; report immediately. HIGH ALERT — double-check required. Inhibits bacterial protein synthesis at 50S ribosomal subunit.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Regular Insulin SQ</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Short-acting insulin</td>
          <td>Onset 30 min / Peak 2–4 hr / Duration 5–8 hr. ALWAYS verify correct insulin TYPE (look-alike/sound-alike risk with other insulins). Independent double-check with second RN before every dose. Ensure patient will eat. Monitor glucose before and 1–2 hr after. Know hypoglycemia response protocol.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Dextrose 50% (D50) IV</strong> <span class="badge-danger">HIGH ALERT</span></td>
          <td>Concentrated glucose solution</td>
          <td>Emergency hypoglycemia treatment for unresponsive patient. <strong>Verify IV patency BEFORE administering</strong> — concentrated glucose causes severe tissue necrosis if extravasation occurs. Give as slow IV push (50 mL over 2–3 min). Recheck glucose 15 min after. HIGH ALERT — requires double-check.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Furosemide (Lasix) PO</strong></td>
          <td>Loop diuretic</td>
          <td>Give in morning to avoid nocturia. Monitor potassium (hypokalemia — loop diuretics waste K⁺). Assess BP before administering — hold for SBP &lt;90. Monitor daily weight and I&amp;O. Hypokalemia impairs wound healing and increases digoxin toxicity risk if applicable.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
