  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Describe the staging of pressure ulcers and appearance at each stage.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>DTI</strong></td><td>Intact skin; persistent purple/maroon non-blanchable discoloration or blood-filled blister; may feel boggy</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 1</strong></td><td>Non-blanchable erythema; intact skin; warm or cool; painful</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 2</strong></td><td>Partial-thickness; shallow open ulcer or serum blister; pink/red bed; no slough</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 3</strong></td><td>Full-thickness; fat visible; crater-like; slough/eschar may be present; no fascia</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Stage 4</strong></td><td>Full-thickness; bone/tendon/muscle exposed; tunneling common</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Unstageable</strong></td><td>Full-thickness; base covered by slough/eschar; depth unknown until debrided</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Describe the four types of wound debridement.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Surgical/Sharp</strong> — scalpel, scissors, curette; fastest; used for large or infected wounds; OR or wound clinic setting; requires sterile field and anesthesia</li>
          <li><strong>Mechanical</strong> — wet-to-dry dressings, irrigation, whirlpool; non-selective (can remove healthy tissue); traditional method</li>
          <li><strong>Enzymatic</strong> — collagenase (Santyl) applied topically; selective; once daily; needs moist environment; moderate speed</li>
          <li><strong>Autolytic</strong> — moisture-retentive dressings (hydrocolloid, hydrogel, transparent films); body's own enzymes dissolve necrotic tissue; most selective; slowest; NOT for infected wounds; most comfortable</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Why do pressure ulcers form and where are they most common?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Cause:</strong> Sustained pressure → reduced blood flow → tissue hypoxia → cell death. Contributing factors: friction, shear, moisture, malnutrition, immobility, diabetes, heart failure.</p>
        <p><strong>Most common locations:</strong> Sacrum/coccyx (most common), heels, greater trochanter, ischial tuberosities (sitting), elbows, occiput, ears.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What are the nursing interventions for a patient with a pressure ulcer?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Turn and reposition q2h — MOST IMPORTANT intervention; use 30-degree lateral tilt</li>
          <li>HOB elevation ≤ 30 degrees (reduces sacral shear)</li>
          <li>Pressure-redistributing mattress (foam, air, gel)</li>
          <li>Elevate heels off mattress; use heel protectors</li>
          <li>Wound care per order with appropriate dressing selection</li>
          <li>Document: location, stage, size (L × W × D cm), wound bed, drainage, periwound skin</li>
          <li>Culture if infection signs present</li>
          <li>Nutrition: high protein, Vit C, Vit A, Zinc; dietitian consult</li>
          <li>Pre-medicate before dressing changes; assess pain response</li>
          <li>Consult WOCN (wound/ostomy/continence nurse)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: How does Type 2 diabetes impair wound healing?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Hyperglycemia impairs neutrophil function → reduced immune response → infection risk</li>
          <li>Peripheral vascular disease (PVD) → reduced blood flow → inadequate O2 and nutrients at wound</li>
          <li>Peripheral neuropathy → cannot feel wound forming or worsening; delayed recognition</li>
          <li>Impaired collagen synthesis → slower wound closure and tensile strength</li>
          <li>High glucose = ideal bacterial growth medium → wound colonization/infection</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q6: What are the RN, LPN, and CNA roles in wound care?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>RN:</strong> Stage and measure wound; full wound assessment (infection, healing progression, complications); create and update plan of care; coordinate with WOCN; educate patient and family; update wound care orders within standing protocols.</p>
        <p><strong>LPN:</strong> Perform dressing changes (per scope of practice and facility policy); assess and document wound characteristics; report changes to RN.</p>
        <p><strong>CNA/NAP:</strong> Alert nurse to skin changes or wound appearance changes; assist with repositioning and hygiene; report patient complaints of pain near wound. <em>Cannot perform wound assessment or dressing changes.</em></p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

